<item>
            <title>[GROOVY-4380] Round-tripping XML which contains a newline character reference in an attribute&apos;s value removes the character reference</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-4380</link>
                <project id="12318123" key="GROOVY">Groovy</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;Given an XML file which contains a newline character reference (&amp;#10;) in the value of an attribute, the following groovy code incorrectly outputs the actual newline character instead of the original character reference. This is a significant problem because the XML standard dictates that newlines found in the value of an attribute must be treated as a space. Thus, if any XML parser reads the output of this groovy snippet, it is as if the newline is gone.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;newline.xml:&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;lt;option name=&quot;LINE_SEPARATOR&quot; value=&quot;&amp;#10;&quot;/&amp;gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;groovy:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;def fileWriter = new FileWriter(&apos;./newline-roundtrip.xml&apos;)&lt;br/&gt;
def input = new XmlParser().parse(&apos;./newline.xml&apos;)&lt;br/&gt;
PrintWriter printWriter = new PrintWriter(fileWriter)&lt;br/&gt;
new XmlNodePrinter(printWriter).print(input)&lt;br/&gt;
printWriter.flush()&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve attached a junit test which demonstrates the problem.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
